{{EngvarB|date=October 2015}} {{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}} '''Edward Vivian Dearman Birchall''' (10 August 1884 – 10 August 1916<ref name=Laybourn />), was an English [[philanthropist]] who died of wounds at the [[Battle of the Somme]]. He left a legacy of £1000 for the promotion of voluntary services. The money was used to help create, in 1919, the National Council of Social Services. It later became the [[National Council for Voluntary Organisations]], an umbrella body for charities in England.<ref name="Smith">{{cite news | url=http://thirdforcenews.org.uk/tfn-news/soldiers-legacy-lives-on-through-a-century-of-voluntary-action | title=Soldier’s legacy lives on through a century of voluntary action | work=Third Force News | date=5 August 2014 | accessdate=1 July 2015 | author=Smith, Susan}}</ref>
He was born on 10 August 1884 at [[Bowden Hall]],<ref group="nb"> Bowden Hall was purchased by the Birchall family in 1868 and is now a hotel. {{cite web|url= http://www.parksandgardens.org/places-and-people/site/5811/history|title= Bowden Hall, (also known as Creed's Place, Bounden Hall and Bowden Hall Ramada Hotel Gloucester), Upton St Leonards, England. Record Id: 5811| publisher= Parks and Gardens UK |date= 4 December 2008 |accessdate=6 July 2015}}</ref> [[Upton St Leonards]], [[Gloucestershire]], the son of Dearman and Emily Jowitt Birchall.<ref name="Laybourn">{{cite book | url=http://oxfordindex.oup.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/68990 | title=Birchall, Edward Vivian Dearman (1884–1916), philanthropist | publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] | work=[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]] | date=September 2004 | accessdate=1 July 2015 | author=Laybourn, Keith}}</ref>
Birchall was a captain in the [[48th (South Midland) Division|1/1st Buckinghamshire Battalion]]. He died on 10 August 1916 and is buried in France, at [[Étaples Military Cemetery]] near [[Boulogne]].
